<subSubSection id="C316C8D5FFBCFFE7FF207F634387509C" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" type="key">
<keyStep id="30F883FBFFBCFFE7FF207F63438452BC" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207F634387526C" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207F634387526C" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
1. Fore femur with 2–7 long posterodorsal setae (
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FD1F7F634586521C" box="[665,715,259,281]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[170,203,1623,1645]" captionTargetBox="[170,1222,175,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[170,1228,170,1606]" captionText="Fig. 3. Eupyrgota pictiventris ♀ (1, 3–7, 9–10, 12–13 — holotype Apyrgota pictiventris; 2, 8, 11 — holotype Adapsilia facialis): 1 — habitus, dorsal; 2 — same, left; 3 — labels; 4–6 — head (4 — left, 5 — anterior, 6 — dorsal view); 7 — wing; 8 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 9 — fore femur; 10, 11 — mid femur; 12 — hind femur; 13 — abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462263/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FD537F6345AD521C" box="[725,736,259,281]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">9</emphasis>
), mid femur with long and dense setae on anteroventral surface and large kidney-like femoral organ in distal one-third of femur; medioventral cape of femoral organ densely white microtrichose (
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FDF17F5945EA524A" box="[631,679,313,335]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[170,203,1623,1645]" captionTargetBox="[170,1222,175,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[170,1228,170,1606]" captionText="Fig. 3. Eupyrgota pictiventris ♀ (1, 3–7, 9–10, 12–13 — holotype Apyrgota pictiventris; 2, 8, 11 — holotype Adapsilia facialis): 1 — habitus, dorsal; 2 — same, left; 3 — labels; 4–6 — head (4 — left, 5 — anterior, 6 — dorsal view); 7 — wing; 8 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 9 — fore femur; 10, 11 — mid femur; 12 — hind femur; 13 — abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462263/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FD367F5945A4524A" box="[688,745,313,335]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">10–11</emphasis>
). Scutellum with one pair of apical setae. Abdominal tergites with wide black pattern. ............................................................................................... 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FBC77F344387526C" box="[1089,1226,339,361]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<taxonomicName id="4C0CE0DDFFBCFFE7FBC77F34438B526C" authorityName="Korneyev" authorityYear="2014" baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[1089,1222,339,361]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Eupyrgota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictiventris">E. pictiventris</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207F0E438452BC" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207F0E438452BC" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">— Fore femur only with short posterodorsal setae not longer than its width, mid femur with short setae on anteroventral surface; femoral organ in female either oval, without white microtrichose parts, or absent. Scutellum with one or two pairs of apical setae. ................................................................................................. 2.</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30F883FBFFBCFFE7FF207FDE438452EA" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207FDE438452D1" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" box="[166,1225,446,468]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207FDE438452D1" box="[166,1225,446,468]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">2. Scutellum with one pair of apical setae. Africa. .................................................................................................. 3.</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207FB9438452EA" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" box="[166,1225,473,495]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207FB9438452EA" box="[166,1225,473,495]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">— Scutellum usually with additional pair of subapical setae half as long as apical. Asia. (Males unknown.) ........... 4.</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30F883FBFFBCFFE7FF207F934387518A" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207F934385513A" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207F934385513A" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
3. 
<title id="F9087068FFBCFFE7FF527F934676513A" jopScore="0.03983666" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
Postpronotal seta and anepisternal setae present; postpronotal lobe with 4–8 setulae. Female: midfemur with femoral organ (Korneyev, 2006 a: 
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FDC97C6E45325121" box="[591,639,526,548]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[170,203,1623,1645]" captionTargetBox="[170,1222,175,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[170,1228,170,1606]" captionText="Fig. 3. Eupyrgota pictiventris ♀ (1, 3–7, 9–10, 12–13 — holotype Apyrgota pictiventris; 2, 8, 11 — holotype Adapsilia facialis): 1 — habitus, dorsal; 2 — same, left; 3 — labels; 4–6 — head (4 — left, 5 — anterior, 6 — dorsal view); 7 — wing; 8 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 9 — fore femur; 10, 11 — mid femur; 12 — hind femur; 13 — abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462263/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FD0F7C6E45D95121" box="[649,660,526,548]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">4</emphasis>
). Oviscape on ventral side with numerous thickened setae (Korneyev
</title>
, 
<year id="FFA4DA0DFFBCFFE7FEC27C49463F513A" box="[324,370,553,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">2006</year>
a: 
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FE0B7C4946F0513A" box="[397,445,553,575]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[170,203,1623,1645]" captionTargetBox="[170,1222,175,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[170,1228,170,1606]" captionText="Fig. 3. Eupyrgota pictiventris ♀ (1, 3–7, 9–10, 12–13 — holotype Apyrgota pictiventris; 2, 8, 11 — holotype Adapsilia facialis): 1 — habitus, dorsal; 2 — same, left; 3 — labels; 4–6 — head (4 — left, 5 — anterior, 6 — dorsal view); 7 — wing; 8 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 9 — fore femur; 10, 11 — mid femur; 12 — hind femur; 13 — abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462263/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<journalOrPublisher id="51CD9192FFBCFFE7FE0B7C4946E1513A" box="[397,428,553,575]" jopScore="0.00519927" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" type="_" typeScore="2">fig.</journalOrPublisher>
3
</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FE407C49469C513A" box="[454,465,553,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<part id="FFA831C3FFBCFFE7FE407C49469C513A" box="[454,465,553,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" type="volume">8</part>
</emphasis>
). 
<author id="53B173BBFFBCFFE7FE637C494451513A" box="[485,796,553,575]" case="TC" fn="Democratic Republic" fnc="TC" fns="N" ln="Nigeria" lnc="TC" npo="LnFn" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" tsw="true">Nigeria, Democratic Republic of</author>
Congo. ....................................... 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FBCC7C494385513A" box="[1098,1224,553,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">E. spinifemur</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207C234387518A" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207C234387518A" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
— 
<author id="53B173BBFFBCFFE7FF527C23461C515C" box="[212,337,579,601]" fns="*" inm="true" npo="*" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">Postpronotal</author>
<title id="F9087068FFBCFFE7FEDF7C2345405171" jopScore="0.033894494" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
seta and anepisternal setae absent; postpronotal lobe with 0–2 setulae. Female: midfemur without femoral organ (
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FE3D7C3E46A65171" box="[443,491,606,628]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[184,1213,188,1567]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,174,1610]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Eupyrgota formosana, ♀: 1–3 — head (1 — left, 2 — anterior, 3 — dorsal view); 4 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 5 — wing; 6 — mid femur, anterior; 7, 8 — abdomen (7 — dorsal, 8 — lateral view); 9 — apex of oviscape." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452963" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452963/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FE7E7C3E454E5171" box="[504,515,606,628]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">6</emphasis>
)
</title>
. 
<journalOrPublisher id="51CD9192FFBCFFE7FD917C3E433F5171" box="[535,1138,606,628]" jopScore="0.021336729" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" type="_" typeScore="2">Oviscape on ventral side with sparse and thin setae (Korneyev</journalOrPublisher>
, 
<year id="FFA4DA0DFFBCFFE7FBFA7C3E43E75171" box="[1148,1194,606,628]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">2006</year>
a): 
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FF527C194649518A" box="[212,260,633,655]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[170,203,1623,1645]" captionTargetBox="[170,1222,175,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[170,1228,170,1606]" captionText="Fig. 3. Eupyrgota pictiventris ♀ (1, 3–7, 9–10, 12–13 — holotype Apyrgota pictiventris; 2, 8, 11 — holotype Adapsilia facialis): 1 — habitus, dorsal; 2 — same, left; 3 — labels; 4–6 — head (4 — left, 5 — anterior, 6 — dorsal view); 7 — wing; 8 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 9 — fore femur; 10, 11 — mid femur; 12 — hind femur; 13 — abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462263/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
fig. 
<part id="FFA831C3FFBCFFE7FF717C194649518A" box="[247,260,633,655]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" type="volume">3</part>
</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FE8B7C19467D518A" box="[269,304,633,655]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<pagination id="B2C565AAFFBCFFE7FE8B7C19467D518A" box="[269,304,633,655]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" type="pagination">1–2</pagination>
</emphasis>
). .................................................................................................................................................. 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FBEC7C194387518A" box="[1130,1226,633,655]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">E. saegeri.</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30F883FBFFBCFFE7FF207CF3438451FC" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207CF3438751C1" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207CF3438751C1" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
4. Female: oviscape geniculate, its narrow apical half sharply bent ventrally (
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FC2A7CF3449351AC" box="[940,990,659,681]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[184,1213,188,1567]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,174,1610]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Eupyrgota formosana, ♀: 1–3 — head (1 — left, 2 — anterior, 3 — dorsal view); 4 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 5 — wing; 6 — mid femur, anterior; 7, 8 — abdomen (7 — dorsal, 8 — lateral view); 9 — apex of oviscape." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452963" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452963/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FC6D7CF344BB51AC" box="[1003,1014,659,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">8</emphasis>
); mid femur without femoral organ. 
<collectingCountry id="F31BDBCEFFBCFFE7FEE17CCE46FC51C1" box="[359,433,686,708]" name="Taiwan" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
. ..................................................................................................................... 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FBC37CCF438751C1" box="[1093,1226,686,708]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<taxonomicName id="4C0CE0DDFFBCFFE7FBC37CCF438B51C1" authorityName="Korneyev" authorityYear="2014" baseAuthorityName="Hennig" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[1093,1222,686,708]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Apyrgota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosana">E. formosana</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207CA9438451FC" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<keyLead id="30FD386BFFBCFFE7FF207CA9438451FC" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
— Female: oviscape evenly bent and narrowed ventrally (
<figureCitation id="133787DBFFBCFFE7FD667CA9445D51DA" box="[736,784,713,735]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[184,1213,188,1567]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1232,174,1610]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Eupyrgota formosana, ♀: 1–3 — head (1 — left, 2 — anterior, 3 — dorsal view); 4 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 5 — wing; 6 — mid femur, anterior; 7, 8 — abdomen (7 — dorsal, 8 — lateral view); 9 — apex of oviscape." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452963" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452963/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B978474CFFBCFFE7FC9A7CA9446A51DA" box="[796,807,713,735]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">8</emphasis>
); mid femur with femoral organ (male unknown). Other regions of Asia. ............................................................................................................................. 5.
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30F883FBFFBCFFE7FF207C9E4387509C" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
<paragraph id="8BB39B5EFFBCFFE7FF207C9E4387504C" blockId="2.[166,1226,259,921]" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">
